<h1>
EURO 2016
</h1>
<h2>
<i> Ronaldo tops list but who is each country’s most valuable player?</i>
</h2>
<P>
Cristiano Ronaldo is the most valuable player at Euro2016.

That is according to the CIES Football Observatory who have the Real Madrid star on top of all the other European aces who<br/> will be competing in France this summer.<br/>

The 31-year-old forward came in third overall in the CIES transfer value chart with a valuation of £107.67million, behind Barcelona<br/> stars Lionel Messi (Argentina) and Neymar (Brazil), but was well clear of Portugal teammate Andre Gomes who came in 53rd on the list.

Second behind Ronaldo in Europe is France forward Antoine Griezmann with a valuation of £93.92m, slightly ahead of England's Harry Kane on £87.90m.


See below to find out who is the most valued player in each of the 24 teams at Euro2016:


Portugal - Cristiano Ronaldo (Real Madrid) - £107.67m<br/>

France - Antoine Griezmann (Atletico Madrid) - £93.92m<br/>

England - Harry Kane (Tottenham) - £87.90m<br/>

Wales - Gareth Bale (Real Madrid) - £63.13m<br/>

Belgium - Eden Hazard (Chelsea) - £61.18m<br/>

Germany - Thomas Muller (Bayern Munich) - £57.43m<br/>

Poland - Robert Lewandowski (Bayern Munich) - £52.98m<br/>

Spain - Alvaro Morata (Juventus) - £50.16m<br/>

Austria - David Alaba (Bayern Munich) - £38.13m<br/>

Croatia - Ivan Rakitic (Barcelona) - £30.71m<br/>

Italy - Leonardo Bonucci (Juventus) - £30.16m<br/>

Switzerland - Granit Xhaka (Arsenal) - £22.50m<br/>

Turkey - Hakan Calhanoglu (Bayer Leverkusen) - £21.25m<br/>

Ukraine - Andriy Yarmolenko (Dynamo Kyiv) - £20.16m<br/>

Albania - Elseid Hysaj (Napoli) - £16.88m<br/>

Slovakia - Marek Hamsik (Napoli) - £15.16m<br/>

Iceland - Gylfi Sigurdsson (Swansea City) - £12.81m<br/>

Russia - Oleg Shatov (Zenit Saint Petersburg) - £11.56m<br/>

Sweden - Emil Forsberg (RB Leipzig) - £11.56m<br/>

Republic of Ireland - James McCarthy (Everton) - £11.33m<br/>

Czech Republic - Petr Cech (Arsenal) - £8.05m<br/>

Northern Ireland - Craig Cathcart (Watford) - £7.11m<br/>

Romania - Florina Andone (Cordoba) - £5.86m<br/>

Hungary - Nemanja Nikolic (Legia Warsaw) - £5.16m<br/>

